6 In coordination with academic and economic actors, it takes measures to
anticipate risks and opportunities, thereby maintaining Switzerland among the
most advanced and secure nations in the digital domain.
6. What Does Being a Member of the Initiative Committee
Involve?
In accordance with federal law, the initiative committee is composed of 7 to 27
members. A balanced representation of cantons and linguistic regions is
sought, reflecting the national character of the initiative.
Being a member of the initiative committee:
• entails no operational responsibilities
• involves no financial commitment
• does not require partisan political engagement or mandatory media exposure
Committee members support the initiative in principle.
Those who wish to contribute further — for example on logistical, legal, or
public-debate matters — are nevertheless welcome to do so.
7. The Popular Initiative Process: Practical Timeline
Like all federal popular initiatives, this proposal follows a clear, transparent, and
well-established democratic process, ensuring that any constitutional
amendment rests on a dual legitimacy: that of the people and that of the
cantons.
The initiative therefore follows a clearly defined democratic process.
Preparation Phase
• formation of an initiative committee
• finalization of the constitutional amendment
• formal review by the Federal Chancellery
• official publication in the Federal Gazette, enabling the collection of
signatures
Signature Collection Phase
• collection of at least 100,000 valid signatures
• maximum fixed duration of 18 months
• certification of signatures by local authorities
Submission and Validation
• submission of all signatures in a single filing
• formal verification and counting
• official confirmation of the initiative’s success
3
Federal Review
• the Federal Council issues a formal opinion and may propose a
counterproposal
• Parliament deliberates following the Federal Council’s position
Popular Vote
• national vote requiring a double majority of the people and the cantons
8. Conclusion
The popular initiative “For the Digital Security of Switzerland” seeks to grant
the Confederation clear constitutional authority to ensure Switzerland’s digital
security and digital sovereignty. This is a fundamental issue for the country’s
independence and for the protection of its citizens in an era of accelerating
digital transformation.
The initiative does not seek to control, regulate, or centralize the digital
domain. Its purpose is to clarify the State’s core responsibilities in a field that
has become essential to collective life.
Swiss citizens must have the right to live in a digitally secure and sovereign
country, where their individual and collective interests are protected.